    "pathophysiology": "Typical HUS: Shiga toxin (Stx) produced by STEC binds to globotriaosylceramide (Gb3) receptors on renal endothelial cells. The toxin is internalized and inhibits protein synthesis, causing endothelial injury and apoptosis. This triggers microvascular thrombosis with platelet-rich thrombi, leading to mechanical fragmentation of RBCs (schistocytes), platelet consumption, and renal cortical necrosis. Atypical HUS: Genetic mutations in complement regulatory proteins (CFH, CFI, MCP) lead to uncontrolled alternative pathway complement activation on endothelial surfaces, causing similar microvascular injury but without diarrheal prodrome.",
